div.head: Hymiskviða [Lay of Hymir] (Excerpt)
div.p: Jörmungandr, the serpent encircles the earth.

Drew up boldly|the mighty Thor|the worm with venom glistening,|up to the side;|with his hammer struck,|on his foul head’s summit,|like a rock towering,|the wolf’s own brother. Jörmungandr and Fenrir are brothers and both sons of Loki.
The icebergs resounded,|the caverns howled,|the old earth|shrank together:|at length the fish|back into the ocean sank.Thor and Jörmungandr are destined to fight during Ragnarok.

div.head: Prose Edda (Excerpt)
div.p: "Loke had yet more children. A giantess in Jotunheim, hight Angerboda. With her he begat three children. The first was the Fenris−wolf; the second, Jormungand, that is, the Midgard−serpent, and the third, Hel.Not to be confused with Hel, one of the underworlds in Norse Mythology. When the gods knew that these three children were being fostered in Jotunheim, and were aware of the prophecies that much woe and misfortune would thence come to them, and considering that much evil might be looked for from them on their mother's side, and still more on their father's, Alfather sent some of the gods to take the children and bring them to him. When they came to him he threw the serpent into the deep sea which surrounds all lands. There waxed the serpent so that he lies in the midst of the ocean, surrounds all the earth, and bites his own tail."
